      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The issue with your current code is that it checks every single substring of the input string, which is inefficient. We can optimize this by considering the expansion around the center of the palindrome. \n\nHere's a revised version of your function:\n\n```python\ndef longest_palindrome(s):\n    def expand_around_center(s, left, right):\n        while left >= 0 and right < len(s) and s[left] == s[right]:\n            left -= 1\n            right += 1\n        return s[left + 1:right]\n\n    n = len(s)\n    res = \"\"\n    for i in range(n):\n        # odd length palindrome\n        odd_palindrome = expand_around_center(s, i, i)\n        # even length palindrome\n        even_palindrome = expand_around_center(s, i, i + 1)\n        res = max([res, odd_palindrome, even_palindrome], key=len)\n    return res\n```\n\nThis version of the function works by expanding around the center of potential palindromes. It checks both odd-length and even-length palindromes, and keeps track of the longest one found so far. This approach significantly reduces the number of substrings that need to be",
